<text>Pair correlation function

Pair correlation function (PCF) characterizes the distribution of other atoms around an atom in an isotropic structure. It is often used to analyze results from X-ray or neutron diffraction experiments. 

Theoretically, the PCFs are defined as: 

  

where a , b stands for the type of atoms, V is the total volume, Na is the number of type a atoms in the system, delta(r) is the Dirac delta function.

Experimentally, the PCF can be obtained from the Fourier transform of the structure factor, which is proportional to the diffraction intensity. The diffraction intensity depends on the angle between the wave vector direction of the incident beam of photons or neutrons and the direction the detector is placed from the sample:
  

g(r) can be obtained from the ensemble average of S(k):

  

The PCF can be used to quantify the structural difference of gas, liquid and solid, as is shown in the following graph: 

  

The left is the PCF of a gas (single peak, no ordering), the middle a liquid (double peaks, short-range ordering), and the right a solid (multiple peaks, long-range ordering).

Also known as radial distribution function.

 
